1
00:00:00,000 --> 00:00:03,560
 - Hello, welcome to Django for Everybody.

2
00:00:03,560 --> 00:00:05,840
 My name is Charles Severance, and I've developed

3
00:00:05,840 --> 00:00:08,100
 these materials that I hope you find useful.

4
00:00:08,100 --> 00:00:10,520
 So one of the things I like to do

5
00:00:10,520 --> 00:00:13,160
 whenever I start teaching a class

6
00:00:13,160 --> 00:00:16,880
 is explain why I chose to teach this material,

7
00:00:16,880 --> 00:00:19,640
 in particular, why Django?

8
00:00:19,640 --> 00:00:22,160
 To explain why Django, I have to go back

9
00:00:22,160 --> 00:00:23,620
 into the past a little bit.

10
00:00:23,620 --> 00:00:28,120
 I have been teaching here at the School of Information,

11
00:00:28,120 --> 00:00:32,400
 University of Michigan since 2007.

12
00:00:32,400 --> 00:00:34,720
 I've been teaching web development.

13
00:00:34,720 --> 00:00:37,920
 And if we go all the way back to the beginning,

14
00:00:37,920 --> 00:00:42,920
 I think we started with PHP, then we did Ruby on Rails,

15
00:00:42,920 --> 00:00:46,400
 and then we did Google App Engine.

16
00:00:46,400 --> 00:00:50,060
 I even wrote a textbook for O'Reilly and Associates

17
00:00:50,060 --> 00:00:51,400
 about Google App Engine.

18
00:00:51,400 --> 00:00:53,440
 We used that textbook for a while.

19
00:00:53,440 --> 00:00:55,800
 That was based on Django 1.0,

20
00:00:55,800 --> 00:00:58,680
 and then they changed Google App Engine,

21
00:00:58,680 --> 00:01:02,560
 and didn't like that 'cause it broke my book.

22
00:01:02,560 --> 00:01:07,560
 And then we switched to PHP, and then we did Flask,

23
00:01:07,560 --> 00:01:10,280
 and then we did Django.

24
00:01:10,280 --> 00:01:12,560
 So there's a whole litany

25
00:01:12,560 --> 00:01:16,000
 of different web development frameworks

26
00:01:16,000 --> 00:01:17,340
 we've used over the years,

27
00:01:17,340 --> 00:01:19,000
 and that's kinda how web development is.

28
00:01:19,000 --> 00:01:22,000
 There's always something new, always something different.

29
00:01:22,000 --> 00:01:27,000
 So right before I was teaching Django for everybody,

30
00:01:27,000 --> 00:01:28,560
 I was teaching PHP,

31
00:01:28,560 --> 00:01:30,800
 and I had been teaching that for five years,

32
00:01:30,800 --> 00:01:33,220
 and I just loved that class.

33
00:01:33,220 --> 00:01:36,600
 We teach Python for most of our beginning students,

34
00:01:36,600 --> 00:01:39,680
 and just that's a great first language.

35
00:01:39,680 --> 00:01:42,520
 That course that I built that taught Python to beginners

36
00:01:42,520 --> 00:01:45,580
 evolved into the course Python for Everybody,

37
00:01:45,580 --> 00:01:48,480
 which is one of the most popular programming courses

38
00:01:48,480 --> 00:01:49,600
 in the world.

39
00:01:49,600 --> 00:01:51,400
 And one of the things that I wanted to do

40
00:01:51,400 --> 00:01:54,800
 was teach a second language, not just more Python.

41
00:01:54,800 --> 00:01:57,440
 So that's why I really like teaching PHP.

42
00:01:57,440 --> 00:02:00,040
 And I developed that course for five years,

43
00:02:00,040 --> 00:02:01,760
 but it wasn't just a PHP class.

44
00:02:01,760 --> 00:02:06,760
 It was HTML, it's CSS, JavaScript, jQuery, JSON, PHP.

45
00:02:06,760 --> 00:02:13,360
 And I loved teaching that class,

46
00:02:13,360 --> 00:02:15,600
 but at some point the curriculum committee

47
00:02:15,600 --> 00:02:18,500
 wanted it to be Python across the board.

48
00:02:18,500 --> 00:02:19,340
 I loved that course,

49
00:02:19,340 --> 00:02:22,040
 and I turned it into web applications for everybody,

50
00:02:22,040 --> 00:02:25,680
 and that's available also online.

51
00:02:25,680 --> 00:02:30,240
 And so I had a year to convert from PHP to Python.

52
00:02:30,240 --> 00:02:34,280
 And so during that year, I asked myself the question,

53
00:02:34,280 --> 00:02:36,040
 would I teach Flask or Django?

54
00:02:36,040 --> 00:02:38,560
 And I had a semester sabbatical,

55
00:02:38,560 --> 00:02:42,160
 and during that time someone taught the class in Flask.

56
00:02:42,160 --> 00:02:44,540
 And I looked at what they were accomplishing

57
00:02:44,540 --> 00:02:46,920
 in the 15th week of the Flask class,

58
00:02:46,920 --> 00:02:49,480
 and I'm like, oh, there's so much low-level stuff

59
00:02:49,480 --> 00:02:50,880
 you have to learn.

60
00:02:50,880 --> 00:02:53,300
 And so I was like, eh, I'm not sure I like Flask.

61
00:02:53,300 --> 00:02:56,520
 But I had a year, so I asked everyone I knew,

62
00:02:56,520 --> 00:02:59,020
 who was pretty sharp, I said,

63
00:02:59,020 --> 00:03:01,640
 would you prefer Flask or Django?

64
00:03:01,640 --> 00:03:04,600
 And the strange thing is I got different answers.

65
00:03:04,600 --> 00:03:07,680
 Half the people said, Flask is great, Django's terrible,

66
00:03:07,680 --> 00:03:10,080
 and the other half the people said, Django's great,

67
00:03:10,080 --> 00:03:12,840
 Flask is terrible, which was inconclusive.

68
00:03:12,840 --> 00:03:14,560
 And then I changed the question.

69
00:03:14,560 --> 00:03:18,160
 I said, if you were gonna teach only one of Flask or Django,

70
00:03:18,160 --> 00:03:19,880
 which one would you teach first?

71
00:03:19,880 --> 00:03:21,760
 And at that point,

72
00:03:21,760 --> 00:03:24,760
 Django was pretty much the consensus agreement.

73
00:03:24,760 --> 00:03:29,760
 And that's because Flask is a very powerful tool

74
00:03:29,760 --> 00:03:33,000
 in the hands of strong developers.

75
00:03:33,000 --> 00:03:37,260
 So if you're taking a React class

76
00:03:37,260 --> 00:03:40,720
 or a Progressive Web Applications class,

77
00:03:40,720 --> 00:03:42,920
 and you just want kind of a little backend,

78
00:03:42,920 --> 00:03:43,960
 and you know what you're doing,

79
00:03:43,960 --> 00:03:46,520
 Flask is great, 'cause you whip up a little microservice

80
00:03:46,520 --> 00:03:47,880
 and away it goes.

81
00:03:47,880 --> 00:03:50,480
 But Django, if you don't know anything,

82
00:03:50,480 --> 00:03:52,040
 Django gives you a road to follow.

83
00:03:52,040 --> 00:03:54,320
 You go down this road, and you will learn,

84
00:03:54,320 --> 00:03:55,800
 and you will build something.

85
00:03:55,800 --> 00:04:00,880
 And so I started developing this class.

86
00:04:00,880 --> 00:04:02,880
 It took me a couple years to get it right.

87
00:04:02,880 --> 00:04:03,920
 I iterate a lot.

88
00:04:03,920 --> 00:04:06,480
 I'm an engineer, and I love to iterate.

89
00:04:06,480 --> 00:04:09,880
 After a couple years, I said, okay, I think I like it.

90
00:04:09,880 --> 00:04:13,680
 And so I turned it into this DJ for E, Django for everybody.

91
00:04:13,680 --> 00:04:14,780
 It became a MOOC.

92
00:04:14,780 --> 00:04:20,800
 And so I'm really impressed at how far we get.

93
00:04:20,800 --> 00:04:23,320
 And the reason is, is with Django,

94
00:04:23,320 --> 00:04:26,960
 because there's kind of a road, and you follow the road.

95
00:04:26,960 --> 00:04:31,520
 At the end, my students have a nicely working website

96
00:04:31,520 --> 00:04:35,320
 that has Ajax working, has pictures working,

97
00:04:35,320 --> 00:04:39,440
 has single sign-on using OAuth working,

98
00:04:39,440 --> 00:04:40,560
 and all these things.

99
00:04:40,560 --> 00:04:43,040
 And we learn about Bootstrap and a whole bunch of things.

100
00:04:43,040 --> 00:04:46,340
 And if you look at their website, it's a beginner,

101
00:04:46,340 --> 00:04:48,300
 but it is a complete website.

102
00:04:48,300 --> 00:04:50,960
 And because we use Python Anywhere,

103
00:04:50,960 --> 00:04:54,440
 they are hosting it from the first week.

104
00:04:54,440 --> 00:04:59,000
 So every assignment is in a hosted Python Anywhere instance

105
00:04:59,000 --> 00:05:00,040
 of Django for them.

106
00:05:00,040 --> 00:05:01,440
 And so they're learning how to host.

107
00:05:01,440 --> 00:05:04,560
 And I think that's, of all the things I've taught

108
00:05:04,560 --> 00:05:08,040
 up to this point, I never, other than Google App Engine,

109
00:05:08,040 --> 00:05:11,800
 I never could get the students to have in effect a URL

110
00:05:11,800 --> 00:05:13,680
 at the end of the course.

111
00:05:13,680 --> 00:05:18,680
 This is a great second class, once you kind of know Python,

112
00:05:18,680 --> 00:05:22,720
 to learn how to use Python to do something.

113
00:05:22,720 --> 00:05:24,560
 It's advanced Python.

114
00:05:24,560 --> 00:05:27,160
 It's using things that you might have seen

115
00:05:27,160 --> 00:05:30,960
 in initial Python class, but not really developed skill in.

116
00:05:30,960 --> 00:05:33,160
 And the particular skill that this class really

117
00:05:33,160 --> 00:05:36,480
 is going to teach you is object-oriented programming.

118
00:05:36,480 --> 00:05:39,620
 And I'll just say, object-oriented programming

119
00:05:39,620 --> 00:05:42,760
 is probably one of the most important concepts

120
00:05:42,760 --> 00:05:47,680
 in programming, and it's also the most difficult concept

121
00:05:47,680 --> 00:05:48,960
 to teach and learn.

122
00:05:48,960 --> 00:05:51,920
 That's because if you just take a class

123
00:05:51,920 --> 00:05:53,820
 and you have a chapter on object orientation,

124
00:05:53,820 --> 00:05:54,960
 you'll see a bunch of syntax,

125
00:05:54,960 --> 00:05:57,360
 but you do not know why you're using that syntax.

126
00:05:57,360 --> 00:06:00,280
 Whereas in Django, on the first day,

127
00:06:00,280 --> 00:06:02,260
 you're building objects.

128
00:06:02,260 --> 00:06:04,160
 Django itself is an object,

129
00:06:04,160 --> 00:06:06,680
 and you're like overriding bits and pieces

130
00:06:06,680 --> 00:06:08,080
 inside of this big object.

131
00:06:08,080 --> 00:06:09,800
 And then there's objects within objects.

132
00:06:09,800 --> 00:06:14,600
 And so it's a wonderful, wonderful way

133
00:06:14,600 --> 00:06:17,280
 to teach object-oriented programming in Django.

134
00:06:17,280 --> 00:06:19,000
 And so in this class,

135
00:06:19,000 --> 00:06:21,960
 I review Python's object-oriented programming.

136
00:06:21,960 --> 00:06:25,040
 I feature all of the use of objects in Django

137
00:06:25,040 --> 00:06:27,400
 when I say object many, many times,

138
00:06:27,400 --> 00:06:29,960
 just like I'm saying in this little intro video.

139
00:06:29,960 --> 00:06:32,920
 But then we also later look at JavaScript,

140
00:06:32,920 --> 00:06:34,960
 and then we look at object-oriented programming

141
00:06:34,960 --> 00:06:36,880
 in JavaScript as well.

142
00:06:36,880 --> 00:06:38,200
 And they're different.

143
00:06:38,200 --> 00:06:40,400
 The execution model for

144
00:06:40,400 --> 00:06:44,880
 Python and the execution model

145
00:06:44,880 --> 00:06:47,160
 for JavaScript object-orientation

146
00:06:47,160 --> 00:06:48,780
 is a little bit different.

147
00:06:48,780 --> 00:06:51,800
 And so for me, that sort of compare and contrast

148
00:06:51,800 --> 00:06:54,800
 is a really great opportunity as a teacher

149
00:06:54,800 --> 00:06:56,600
 to get students to understand

150
00:06:56,600 --> 00:06:59,040
 the core principles of object-orientation

151
00:06:59,040 --> 00:07:02,560
 and not be just looking at the various syntaxes.

152
00:07:02,560 --> 00:07:04,540
 So with that, welcome to a course

153
00:07:04,540 --> 00:07:06,280
 that I think is a great course,

154
00:07:06,280 --> 00:07:08,000
 and I hope that you enjoy it.

155
00:07:08,000 --> 00:07:09,660
 And I wish you luck.

156
00:07:09,660 --> 00:07:11,040
 Take your time.

157
00:07:11,040 --> 00:07:12,080
 Don't rush.

158
00:07:12,080 --> 00:07:16,040
 These kind of learning experiences are precious.

159
00:07:16,040 --> 00:07:18,040
 And take your time and learn everything.

160
00:07:18,040 --> 00:07:20,600
 And I wish you nothing but the best,

161
00:07:20,600 --> 00:07:22,440
 and hope to see you online.

162
00:07:22,440 --> 00:07:23,280
 Cheers.

163
00:07:23,280 --> 00:07:25,860
 (upbeat music)

